<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-785-048  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 785 048.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  August 20 1990 v35 n17 p195(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>An engineer's guide to industrial design. (Professional Issues)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fraser, Jay.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A product's design is much more important to its ultimate successin the market than many engineers suspect.andP;  The IndustrialDesigners Society of America estimates that every dollar spent bya company on design generates about $2,500 in sales.andP;  ProductGenesis Inc executive Victor Cheung says the housing of a productcommunicates to consumers, who have no idea whether the product iswell-engineered or not; if the design communicates high quality toconsumers, then they will buy it with confidence.andP;  Industrialdesign should be involved in the development of a product from itsinception to the time it is ready to hit the market.andP;  Industrialdesign firms may work only on product and packaging design or theymay offer such services as electronic and mechanical engineering,market research, prototype development, documentation and thecreation of logos and letterheads.andP;  The services offered byseveral specific industrial design firms and problems encounteredin the industrial design process are examined.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     PackagingMarketing ResearchConsumer BehaviorDesignProduct DevelopmentEngineering Services.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>